249
00:14:42,083 --> 00:14:43,984
That's how kind of Level of Awesome was born.

250
00:14:45,929 --> 00:14:47,590
So you go back to the question,

251
00:14:47,610 --> 00:14:50,193
like, how do we let the player feel more awesome and powerful

252
00:14:50,593 --> 00:14:52,114
as they traverse the world?

253
00:14:52,174 --> 00:14:55,718
So we answer that by utilizing Wwise's switch event system

254
00:14:55,778 --> 00:14:59,321
to change completely the audio of the player's movements

255
00:14:59,561 --> 00:15:01,002
as they gain levels in their style tier.

256
00:15:03,344 --> 00:15:06,167
So the next thing we're gonna talk about

257
00:15:06,207 --> 00:15:08,449
is our design goals for the Level of Awesome system.

258
00:15:10,723 --> 00:15:14,105
The main goal we wanted to achieve was we wanted to have stylized gameplay feedback

259
00:15:14,145 --> 00:15:15,665
as the player traversed through the world.

260
00:15:17,226 --> 00:15:19,527
When you start off the game, you start at level zero.

261
00:15:19,587 --> 00:15:21,708
It's just kind of from the get-go.

262
00:15:22,068 --> 00:15:25,509
And we just wanted to make this kind of intimate and realistic.

263
00:15:25,549 --> 00:15:30,411
So it's just realistic foley, no added movement, only maybe in certain places where we wanted

264
00:15:30,451 --> 00:15:32,632
to emphasize some movement, but it was just kind of basic.

265
00:15:33,152 --> 00:15:37,254
But then as we went to level one, we wanted to introduce our next design goal, which was

266
00:15:37,314 --> 00:15:38,575
having cinematic content.

267
00:15:39,135 --> 00:15:42,197
So we just wanted to add more weight and more

268
00:15:42,217 --> 00:15:44,158
of that cinematic flair to the movement,

269
00:15:44,519 --> 00:15:46,440
just to make the movement more exciting.

270
00:15:47,561 --> 00:15:49,582
And then once the player hits level two,

271
00:15:49,942 --> 00:15:52,784
we wanted to have another layer of fun

272
00:15:52,804 --> 00:15:54,486
to fill out the audio spectrum.

273
00:15:54,906 --> 00:15:59,389
And so we added an old school ninja movie style audio.

274
00:15:59,449 --> 00:16:02,892
So really nice high end swishes, just

275
00:16:02,932 --> 00:16:06,494
to give more speed to the player as they're traversing.

276
00:16:07,319 --> 00:16:10,342
And then, lastly, level three, once you hit your max level,

277
00:16:11,102 --> 00:16:14,265
we wanted to introduce retro 8-bit style audio

278
00:16:14,305 --> 00:16:16,486
with hyper-realistic cartoon realism.

279
00:16:17,207 --> 00:16:19,409
And we like to call that organic cartoon realism.

280
00:16:20,730 --> 00:16:22,831
But lastly, our last goal, we wanted to make sure

281
00:16:22,851 --> 00:16:24,232
that we kept everything clean

282
00:16:24,352 --> 00:16:25,734
and it didn't clutter the experience,

283
00:16:25,774 --> 00:16:28,796
because with all the scope that we wanted to fulfill,

284
00:16:29,176 --> 00:16:29,957
that was the danger of...

285
00:16:30,437 --> 00:16:32,099
we had the danger of kind of cluttering everything.

286
00:16:32,119 --> 00:16:33,820
So we wanted to make sure that everything was clear,

287
00:16:34,180 --> 00:16:35,021
distinct, and felt good.

288
00:16:36,540 --> 00:16:39,545
So here's our design matrix for the Level 3 Awesome.

289
00:16:40,046 --> 00:16:43,591
This was the level where we kind of had a lot more fun,

290
00:16:43,611 --> 00:16:47,757
because we could add things that normal games wouldn't play in their audio.

291
00:16:48,778 --> 00:16:50,761
So how do we make the game sound more fun and awesome?

292
00:16:51,081 --> 00:16:52,664
Well, we were heavily influenced by...

293
00:16:53,365 --> 00:16:55,186
The classic Looney Tunes style audio.

294
00:16:55,287 --> 00:16:57,048
So, like, when you're watching Bugs Bunny,

295
00:16:57,228 --> 00:16:58,750
and they're hitting each other,

296
00:16:58,790 --> 00:17:00,451
there's, like, lots of percussive sounds,

297
00:17:00,792 --> 00:17:02,593
kind of these non-literal moments,

298
00:17:02,974 --> 00:17:06,517
just to kind of sell the humor and the funness of the cartoon.

299
00:17:06,897 --> 00:17:09,720
So we wanted to take that influence and that style

300
00:17:09,780 --> 00:17:11,261
and apply it to Sunset Overdrive.

301
00:17:11,762 --> 00:17:13,043
So we really had to figure out, you know,

302
00:17:13,083 --> 00:17:16,006
what's the language of level 3 awesome for Sunset Overdrive?

303
00:17:16,186 --> 00:17:16,326
Well...

304
00:17:16,987 --> 00:17:19,208
We wanted to make sure that the motions evolved.

305
00:17:19,308 --> 00:17:22,069
On the left side of the screen, you can see we listed

306
00:17:22,309 --> 00:17:24,590
every single action the player can take while they're

307
00:17:24,610 --> 00:17:25,031
traversing.

308
00:17:26,091 --> 00:17:30,093
And we wanted to see what audio can we add to the sound

309
00:17:30,133 --> 00:17:31,234
to kind of sell that motion.

310
00:17:31,334 --> 00:17:34,215
So for example, when the player is falling from a great

311
00:17:34,235 --> 00:17:38,617
distance, when you're at level 0, 1, 2, it's just kind of

312
00:17:38,677 --> 00:17:40,378
fully flapping, some wind in the air.

313
00:17:40,618 --> 00:17:41,239
But once you hit level 3.

314
00:17:42,522 --> 00:17:45,783
We added a jet, the sound of a kind of a shepherd's tone,

315
00:17:46,143 --> 00:17:48,844
jet falling sound, just to kind of have that fun moment when you're falling.

316
00:17:49,605 --> 00:17:55,567
For vaulting, we added more of the speed of kind of ricochets off of an object.

317
00:17:55,867 --> 00:17:59,269
So we just took the old style Western kind of bullet ricochet

318
00:17:59,349 --> 00:18:01,990
and added that in the mix, just to kind of help sell that motion

319
00:18:02,050 --> 00:18:03,331
and make that motion more fun.

320
00:18:04,411 --> 00:18:09,214
And so, lastly, we really wanted to put that 8-bit retro feel to the game,

321
00:18:09,534 --> 00:18:13,196
but we wanted to pick the moments that we can do the most damage

322
00:18:13,216 --> 00:18:15,097
or make the most influence in the game.

323
00:18:15,597 --> 00:18:19,439
So we added them to the big moments in combat, so impacts.

324
00:18:21,160 --> 00:18:23,841
Yeah, impacts, and then when you're falling from great height,

325
00:18:24,241 --> 00:18:25,882
we decided to have the land sounds.

326
00:18:26,902 --> 00:18:30,024
We added an 8-bit flare to the actual impact of the land.

327
00:18:32,407 --> 00:18:39,191
So some of the tools that we used to achieve the 8-bit style audio was the plug-in Chipsounds.

328
00:18:39,851 --> 00:18:43,273
It's a really awesome plug-in that we love to use.

329
00:18:44,073 --> 00:18:47,855
We used an OP1, which is just a really awesome synth.

330
00:18:48,415 --> 00:18:51,317
That we, like, I needed an excuse to buy it,

331
00:18:51,337 --> 00:18:54,600
so this was a great excuse to use for work.

332
00:18:54,780 --> 00:18:56,441
But basically, you can take sounds.

333
00:18:56,501 --> 00:18:57,842
It's almost like a portable hard drive

334
00:18:57,862 --> 00:19:00,524
where you can take sounds and source and put it in there

335
00:19:00,564 --> 00:19:03,766
and just kind of just destroy and have fun with the synths.

336
00:19:03,806 --> 00:19:04,767
So we had a lot of fun with that.

337
00:19:05,247 --> 00:19:06,348
And also, we used a lot of source

338
00:19:06,388 --> 00:19:08,269
from the Sci-Fi Boom Library.

339
00:19:10,991 --> 00:19:13,413
So here's a quick glimpse of the Wwise data structure

340
00:19:13,433 --> 00:19:14,154
for Level of Awesome.

341
00:19:15,061 --> 00:19:20,404
On the left side, you can see one of the things we wanted to make sure we achieved in Chaos

342
00:19:20,424 --> 00:19:25,928
Squad, which is Sunset Overdrive's multiplayer mode, all the characters use the same hero

343
00:19:25,948 --> 00:19:26,188
event.

344
00:19:26,228 --> 00:19:30,110
So we wanted to make sure that we were able to switch between when the remote player was

345
00:19:30,150 --> 00:19:32,391
playing sounds and when the local player was playing sounds.

346
00:19:32,612 --> 00:19:35,693
Because we only want to hear you when you're playing.

347
00:19:35,814 --> 00:19:39,456
We only want to hear the Level Awesome sounds on the player and not on other players because

348
00:19:39,516 --> 00:19:40,857
it would just clutter the mix.

349
00:19:41,277 --> 00:19:43,318
So as you can see, we had a local remote switch.

350
00:19:44,299 --> 00:19:45,259
for the first level.

351
00:19:45,359 --> 00:19:46,120
And then underneath that,

352
00:19:46,160 --> 00:19:48,522
we actually had the Level of Awesome system.

353
00:19:49,122 --> 00:19:50,963
So on the right side, you can see we had our sounds

354
00:19:51,023 --> 00:19:53,205
for AirDash in this example

355
00:19:53,285 --> 00:19:54,826
for level 0, 1, 2, and 3.

356
00:19:57,768 --> 00:19:59,949
From there, we set our switch type event group

357
00:20:00,049 --> 00:20:01,751
to Level of Awesome, or LOA,

358
00:20:02,211 --> 00:20:04,192
and we just set our switch, our default switch,

359
00:20:04,232 --> 00:20:05,373
to no LOA.

360
00:20:06,234 --> 00:20:09,096
And from there, we can assign the different containers

361
00:20:09,196 --> 00:20:11,237
to the switches for each Level of Awesome.

362
00:20:12,724 --> 00:20:16,025
And here is the video showcasing our level awesome system.

363
00:21:29,794 --> 00:21:37,224
I'm not sure what the point of this is.

364
00:21:37,244 --> 00:21:42,911
I'm not sure what the point of this is. It's just a game.

365
00:21:42,991 --> 00:21:44,433
It's just a game.

366
00:22:15,958 --> 00:22:16,198
Thanks.

367
00:22:16,799 --> 00:22:21,203
So another core element in the traversal system was grinding.

368
00:22:22,223 --> 00:22:26,768
Insomniac worked very heavily on this to create a really cool material, like, switching-based

369
00:22:26,808 --> 00:22:32,232
system for when you're grinding on rails versus, you know, wood railways and things of that

370
00:22:32,292 --> 00:22:32,633
nature.

371
00:22:33,253 --> 00:22:36,696
But really, kind of late in production, we ended up...

372
00:22:38,495 --> 00:22:43,158
We ended up wanting to create a more interactive experience,

373
00:22:43,178 --> 00:22:45,259
but we were actually post-code complete.

374
00:22:45,699 --> 00:22:48,021
So we couldn't get any additional engineering time.

375
00:22:48,821 --> 00:22:51,903
So Christopher Melroth, one of our audio directors,

376
00:22:52,123 --> 00:22:54,805
and Jeffrey Domkowski, who's an extremely talented sound

377
00:22:54,825 --> 00:22:58,226
designer at Microsoft, ended up setting up

378
00:22:58,287 --> 00:23:03,089
an entirely event-driven RTPC changing value

379
00:23:03,109 --> 00:23:04,770
for when you're grinding.

380
00:23:06,292 --> 00:23:11,557
And this would drive a YawRTPC value of a minus 90 to positive 90 value

381
00:23:11,817 --> 00:23:12,878
when you're undergrinding.

382
00:23:13,279 --> 00:23:17,102
So depending on the angle of the player character,

383
00:23:17,202 --> 00:23:20,145
you would be able to drive things like EQ changes or...

384
00:23:22,808 --> 00:23:28,011
Things of that nature just to get a little bit of a more interactive experience and help make it feel better.

385
00:23:28,951 --> 00:23:33,093
We also drove pitch changes based on the horizontal speed of the player.

386
00:23:33,753 --> 00:23:37,675
So as you're doing your grind boost, you get that sense of really speeding up.

387
00:23:40,660 --> 00:23:43,481
And we also did gain changes between high and low loops.

388
00:23:43,922 --> 00:23:49,805
So as you would start to increase speed, we could bring in a more intense sound that made

389
00:23:49,825 --> 00:23:51,186
you feel like you were going faster.

390
00:23:51,886 --> 00:23:54,668
So here's kind of a look at our Wwise data structure.

391
00:23:55,488 --> 00:24:01,689
You can see we have a top switch container that would then drive material switches.

392
00:24:02,549 --> 00:24:09,351
And then if we looked at that top level container, we were driving makeup gain changes as well

393
00:24:09,411 --> 00:24:13,332
as pitch changes to get that increased speed that we were talking about.

394
00:24:14,412 --> 00:24:21,113
We also drove EQ changes at that container level, and essentially we would drive two

395
00:24:21,153 --> 00:24:24,194
different gains on two different bands.

396
00:24:25,014 --> 00:24:28,117
And this is how the RTPC looked on the EQ.

397
00:24:29,318 --> 00:24:33,301
And here's an example of how that ended up turning out in game.

398
00:24:33,681 --> 00:24:38,365
But I just want to stress the amount of work that went in to get this in the game.

399
00:24:38,705 --> 00:24:44,690
Because you have to imagine every single grinding animation having to have a unique sound event

400
00:24:44,770 --> 00:24:50,715
set up that would essentially go, what do I need this yaw RTPC value to be and how fast

401
00:24:50,755 --> 00:24:51,916
do I need it to change?

402
00:24:52,977 --> 00:24:53,697
And here's the video.

403
00:25:42,839 --> 00:25:44,781
All right, just to wrap up this portion of the talk

404
00:25:44,881 --> 00:25:46,723
of Level of Awesome, we want to talk about are we happy.

405
00:25:46,903 --> 00:25:49,645
Well, I think we're really happy with the way it turned out.

406
00:25:49,986 --> 00:25:51,487
When it's working, you can really hear it.

407
00:25:51,567 --> 00:25:53,269
And I think it's really rewarding for the player,

408
00:25:53,809 --> 00:25:56,272
the player that's, you know, doing the making fun,

409
00:25:56,512 --> 00:25:58,053
or having fun and, you know, traversing

410
00:25:58,073 --> 00:25:59,054
and comboing together.

411
00:25:59,535 --> 00:26:01,457
It almost, it rewards them for being awesome.

412
00:26:01,717 --> 00:26:03,439
And it also kind of incentivizes them

413
00:26:03,519 --> 00:26:05,200
to keep that style tier high

414
00:26:05,240 --> 00:26:07,763
so they can have that fun factor just always going.

415
00:26:09,139 --> 00:26:10,200
Some of the things we could have hit up.

416
00:26:10,280 --> 00:26:12,302
So one of the things we really wanted to support

417
00:26:12,342 --> 00:26:14,404
that was one of our core designs

418
00:26:14,444 --> 00:26:17,686
was being able to track the end of grind rails

419
00:26:17,846 --> 00:26:19,708
and to also have a lead-in

420
00:26:19,748 --> 00:26:21,750
when you're about to make an impact on the ground.

421
00:26:22,170 --> 00:26:24,752
So we just wanted to have that extra player feedback

422
00:26:24,832 --> 00:26:27,554
just to let them know, hey, I need to stop grinding

423
00:26:27,594 --> 00:26:28,655
and move on to something else.

424
00:26:29,436 --> 00:26:31,337
And also have that cinematic flare

425
00:26:31,638 --> 00:26:33,559
as if when they're about to hit the ground,

426
00:26:33,579 --> 00:26:34,900
we get that nice little whoosh.

427
00:26:36,622 --> 00:26:43,865
This was a hard code tracking task that if we had maybe another month, maybe two, maybe less,

428
00:26:44,026 --> 00:26:47,728
we probably could have achieved, but we just ran out of time, so we didn't get to hit it.

429
00:26:49,288 --> 00:26:55,692
So then, one thing we would have done a little differently is I think we would have had even more fun with the level 3 content.

430
00:26:55,712 --> 00:26:58,353
We would have had more contextual, non-literal moments.

431
00:26:58,913 --> 00:27:01,855
What the consensus was with the team was that...

432
00:27:02,615 --> 00:27:07,297
with our original previous videos was that it added too much of a comical element to the game.

433
00:27:07,417 --> 00:27:09,959
And so we were kind of trying to achieve a more mature style game.

434
00:27:10,679 --> 00:27:15,101
But after the reception of the fans and the players, how much they loved the style of the game,

435
00:27:15,361 --> 00:27:18,642
we really think we could have gone a little bit more, maybe just had more fun with the style

436
00:27:18,802 --> 00:27:20,983
to make the system more distinguishable.

437
00:27:22,593 --> 00:27:26,855
So the next thing we want to talk, and that leads us into our vanity system.

438
00:27:28,035 --> 00:27:33,177
The vanity system, there was a really heavy emphasis, even from the beginning of the project,

439
00:27:33,537 --> 00:27:35,158
to just be who you are.

440
00:27:36,559 --> 00:27:42,381
They really want to support the player's freedom, and the art team did such an amazing job at

441
00:27:42,401 --> 00:27:47,222
Insomniac creating just so much different, unique content that the player can wear.

442
00:27:47,523 --> 00:27:49,063
And we really wanted to showcase this.

443
00:27:50,258 --> 00:27:51,939
So what did that mean for audio?

444
00:27:53,159 --> 00:27:56,841
So we ended up creating a limb-based switching system

445
00:27:56,941 --> 00:28:00,503
to be able to support all the different unique configurations

446
00:28:00,523 --> 00:28:02,324
of the outfits that you could actually put on.

447
00:28:03,304 --> 00:28:06,165
What that meant is we ended up having different switch groups.

448
00:28:06,666 --> 00:28:08,507
And we could have switchable content

449
00:28:08,607 --> 00:28:12,569
based on your torso, your torso front, which was essentially

450
00:28:12,629 --> 00:28:16,230
like jewelry or necklaces, your torso back,

451
00:28:16,270 --> 00:28:17,571
if you put on a backpack.

452
00:28:19,012 --> 00:28:22,740
We would support your legs, your arms, your waist, your feet.

453
00:28:22,880 --> 00:28:27,710
All of that could be uniquely changed at any given point in time.

454
00:28:29,039 --> 00:28:31,941
The nice thing about this system was that we,

455
00:28:33,041 --> 00:28:35,403
we built it in a way that the pipeline was

456
00:28:35,463 --> 00:28:38,625
really effective and efficient and actually didn't require a

457
00:28:39,125 --> 00:28:40,186
ton of code support.

458
00:28:40,826 --> 00:28:42,588
So a lot of people are used to coders

459
00:28:42,648 --> 00:28:45,710
having to go drive all their unique switches.

460
00:28:46,150 --> 00:28:47,731
Any time you need a new one added,

461
00:28:47,791 --> 00:28:50,853
but Insomniac was able to build a system for us

462
00:28:50,933 --> 00:28:53,615
that enabled the designers to be able to go and

463
00:28:53,775 --> 00:28:56,117
add switch groups or drive switches.

464
00:28:57,838 --> 00:29:01,279
Any time we wanted on any unique piece of clothing at any given point in time.

465
00:29:01,779 --> 00:29:03,919
So audio design goals for this system.

466
00:29:04,519 --> 00:29:08,560
We wanted the hero to be unique based on whatever outfit they were wearing.

467
00:29:09,680 --> 00:29:14,461
We really wanted to push how many different sounds we could get out of different clothing types.

468
00:29:15,361 --> 00:29:16,881
Which is harder than it sounds.

469
00:29:17,542 --> 00:29:21,162
A lot of materials end up sounding very similar and the same,

470
00:29:21,282 --> 00:29:26,903
so we really worked hard to try and just create as much unique and identifiable content as possible.

471
00:29:28,272 --> 00:29:32,196
We wanted the audio to always mirror the choices that the player was making.

472
00:29:32,536 --> 00:29:34,057
We really think the player matters.

473
00:29:34,858 --> 00:29:38,681
We really want to make them feel like their decisions are important

474
00:29:38,941 --> 00:29:42,344
and that that drives the experience of what they're having.

475
00:29:42,944 --> 00:29:47,468
And we wanted to support a high level of detail through the hero actions.

476
00:29:47,748 --> 00:29:51,371
So, as you'll see in a bit, we supported a lot of different behaviors

477
00:29:52,012 --> 00:29:53,633
that were completely configurable.

478
00:29:54,287 --> 00:29:59,148
depending on which pieces of clothing you wanted to support at any given point in time.

479
00:30:00,209 --> 00:30:04,990
What this meant, we ended up supporting about nine different behaviors on your hands, one

480
00:30:05,090 --> 00:30:11,553
for your arms when you're falling and flailing in the air, and about 16 different behaviors

481
00:30:11,653 --> 00:30:13,593
for any other limb set.

482
00:30:15,171 --> 00:30:20,093
We supported material switching on the feet as well as shoe type.

483
00:30:21,394 --> 00:30:25,316
We also wanted to ensure that the pipeline was really quick and efficient.

484
00:30:26,217 --> 00:30:31,240
We wanted to make sure that our designers were spending more time in the studio focusing

485
00:30:31,300 --> 00:30:36,743
on content rather than working in the tools to have to just hook up the content, because

486
00:30:36,763 --> 00:30:39,164
it was a very large number of assets.

487
00:30:40,252 --> 00:30:44,273
We also wanted to ensure that your audio would prioritize based on visibility.

488
