00:35:34,908 --> 00:35:38,309
Yes, so as you can see, we had some lofty goals and some big ideas.

573
00:35:38,849 --> 00:35:42,971
And so our first pass we did, we did a complete pass in all the hero animations with a complete

574
00:35:43,011 --> 00:35:46,712
outfit, something that was kind of the default outfit in the game.

575
00:35:46,752 --> 00:35:51,313
So just the top, pants, shoes, and some accessories for the player.

576
00:35:52,014 --> 00:35:54,715
And once we were tagging the animations, we realized that it wasn't...

577
00:35:55,356 --> 00:35:57,918
our initial implementation wasn't limb-based at all.

578
00:35:58,458 --> 00:36:01,780
It was based on animation tags per limb.

579
00:36:02,381 --> 00:36:04,342
So this required about nine different steps

580
00:36:04,682 --> 00:36:07,784
to actually tag animations through the animation.

581
00:36:08,325 --> 00:36:10,186
And we also had to deal with something

582
00:36:10,466 --> 00:36:12,648
similar to Unreal's Kismet scripting

583
00:36:12,728 --> 00:36:13,949
for each article of clothing.

584
00:36:14,389 --> 00:36:17,251
And then for each new behavior that we wanted to support,

585
00:36:17,291 --> 00:36:18,352
we had to have co-support.

586
00:36:19,012 --> 00:36:19,512
So, you know...

587
00:36:21,262 --> 00:36:23,503
As you can see, like, with our scope of the game,

588
00:36:23,584 --> 00:36:24,844
we wouldn't be able to complete the game

